{
  "target": "bootstrap_to_paired_data",
  "kind": "bootstrap_to_paired_data",
  "source_test": "HEC.FDA.ModelTest/integrationtests/StudyDataAnalyticalFrequencyResultsTests.cs (LP3 distribution parameters, LogPearson3(3.537, .438, .075, 125)) + HEC.FDA.ModelTest/unittests/extensions/ContinuousDistributionExtensionsShould.cs (BootstrapToPairedData shape: increasing Xvals/Yvals). No upstream unit test asserts the iterationNumber-overload's exact Yvals, so both cases here are oracle-gate-reproduced directly against ContinuousDistributionExtensions.BootstrapToPairedData(this ContinuousDistribution, long iterationNumber, double[] ExceedanceProbabilities, bool computeIsDeterministic) via the emitter.",
  "note": "construct is {mean, standard_deviation, skew, sample_size} for LogPearson3(mean, standard_deviation, skew, sample_size). exceedance_probabilities is always hecfda::statistics::distributions::required_exceedance_probabilities() (DoubleGlobalStatics.RequiredExceedanceProbabilities, 173 descending values, ported once in double_global_statics.hpp and shared with GraphicalFrequencyUncertaintyCalculators -- see continuous_distribution_extensions.hpp); no case needs a different probability grid, so the array is never restated per-case. Case 'deterministic_lp3' calls bootstrap_to_paired_data(lp3, iteration_number=1, required_exceedance_probabilities(), compute_is_deterministic=true) -- iteration_number is present but UNUSED on this path (matches the C# `if (computeIsDeterministic) bootstrap = continuousDistribution;` branch, which never calls Sample), asserting the resulting PairedData's Yvals: increasing discharge values straight from LP3's own fitted InverseCDF, no RNG involved. Case 'seeded_lp3_bootstrap' first calls generate_random_samples_of_numbers(seed=1234, quantity_of_samples=5) (1234 is the FREQUENCY_SEED constant the Phase 5 EAD compute uses for the analytical flow-frequency curve; quantity_of_samples=5 only needs to exceed iteration_number=1, kept small to bound the fixture) -- pre-generating, per generated-sample slot, SampleSize=125 uniform draws each via the ported .NET Random(seed) sequence -- then bootstrap_to_paired_data(lp3, iteration_number=1, required_exceedance_probabilities(), compute_is_deterministic=false), which resamples LP3 via Sample(1): 125 InverseCDF draws off RandomSamplesofNumbers[1], refit through LogPearson3.Fit(samples) (a fresh log-Pearson-III moment fit over the bootstrap sample), then InverseCDF(1-exceedanceProb) evaluated against THAT refit distribution. This proves the seeded parametric bootstrap reproduces the real C# RandomSamplesofNumbers[iterationNumber] resample bit-for-bit -- the exact seeded path Task 8's ImpactAreaScenarioSimulation.PopulateRandomNumbers/GetFrequencyStageSample uses for an analytical (non-graphical) flow-frequency curve. Both cases assert only Yvals (173 values, mode vector) -- Xvals are the pure formula `1 - exceedance_probabilities[i]`, identical across both cases and not itself a C#-behavioral oracle (see continuous_distribution_extensions.hpp's bootstrap_to_paired_data for the formula), so not separately asserted here. All expected vectors PIN (gate-captured, never hand-derived) -- the seeded case is a bootstrap-resampled distribution refit, not a closed-form value.",
